Presteigje, Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Peak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peak","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places in different parts of England named in Old English with <i>pēac</i> ‘hill, knoll, peak’, includingPeak (Hill) in Sidmouth (Devon), East and West Peek in Luffincot (Devon), a minor locality in Chiddingly (Sussex) once called <i>Peke</i> (now Peke's House), and the Peak District, an area of rugged hills in northwest Derbyshire and adjacent counties.","English: possibly a nickname from the Middle English word in 1 above, denoting a stout, thick-set man.","English: shortened form of   Peacock  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Anton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Common European form of   Anthony   (see cognates list), now also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Anthony","meanings":["The usual English form of the old Roman family name <i>Antonius</i>, which is of uncertain (probably Etruscan) origin. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> (not normally reflected in the pronunciation) represents a learned but erroneous attempt to associate it with Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. In the post-classical period it was a common name, borne by various early saints, most notably a 3rd-century Egyptian hermit monk, who is regarded as the founder of Christian monasticism."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Anton Peake I was born in 1489, in Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales as the son of Sir Hugh Upton II. He married Lady Elizabeth Jane Cowdrey in 1514, in Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1515, in his hometown, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1489–1515":"1489–1515","1485–1517":"1485–1517","1504–1552":"1504–1552","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1514":"1514","1489":"1489","1552":"1552","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","15 May 1504":"15. mai 1504","1517":"1517","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales","Presteigne with Discoed, Presteigje, Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1489–1515":"1489–1515","1485–1517":"1485–1517","1504–1552":"1504–1552","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1514":"1514","1489":"1489","1552":"1552","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","15 May 1504":"15. toukokuuta 1504","1517":"1517","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales","Presteigne with Discoed, Presteigje, Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1489–1515":"1489–1515","1485–1517":"1485–1517","1504–1552":"1504–1552","1440–Male":"1440–Décédé","1514":"1514","1489":"1489","1552":"1552","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","15 May 1504":"15 mai 1504","1517":"1517","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Galles","Presteigne with Discoed, Presteigje, Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Anton Peake I est né en 1489, à Presteigne, Radnorshire, Galles, fils de Sir Hugh Upton II. Il a épousé Lady Elizabeth Jane Cowdrey en 1514, à Presteigne, Radnorshire, Galles. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1515, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 26 ans."},"de":{"1489–1515":"1489–1515","1485–1517":"1485–1517","1504–1552":"1504–1552","1440–Male"